Endorsements: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1mLJ_V9vVIOIHmt_yr9AWrHRPBwyDnyG0/view?usp=sharing
Discussion:
Jeff #1: announcing idea of endorsing candidate in Jan-Feb is premature -will they have the funds to make it to primary?
Robert- may split vote in some metro districts if we don’t endorse and 2 republican candidates go through if early endorsing doesn’t happen.
Beth: can’t advertise fact they were an endorsee bc there wouldn’t be enough time if we don''t do it early
Jeff #2: no way to unendorse a candidate if too early, Republicans can use it against us. Need a provision for that. 
Jeff #3: Regarding 3.2 Proxy votes should not be allowed (60% of the entire committee, not just those present at the meeting) THIS NEEDS TO BE ADDED to ENDORSEMENT PROCESS DOCUMENT- not on there
Mike: Regarding 3.2 Need to ask for resignations of those not attending meetings 
Rasean: Have we looked at other cities and seen how they do their endorsements? 
Jason: Next closest city is Lexington and they do not do endorsements. Most cities do not endorse. 
Logan: process based on how political activist groups in the Louisville area go about endorsing. Per last KDP conversation they may change by-laws to say cities can endorse.
Robert: endorsing is a response to Republicans changing nonpartisan elections 
Voting on Specific Language for Motion: 
Step 3, section 2- proxies will not be permitted
Motion: Mike Ward, seconded Beth Thorpe, motion carries
Add on friendly amendment- 60% of body (currently occupied positions) is needed.
Motion: Max Morley seconded Allison , motion passes

Motion made to accept Endorsements document with 3.2 amendment.

Motion: Mike Ward
Seconded: Beth Thorpe


Nay: 1 (Jeff Noble), 1 abstain (Larry Owens)
Motion passes.

Candidate Recruitment: need East End candidates, recommend names to Robert Kahne

Platform: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1HvlbOXXIPcgSEBYkqRh7mhHbOeOryKgx/edit
Comments- limited to major concerns
Robert- need intro and kicker removal
Beth- need more in Civil Rights, don’t name anything specifically.  Have Labor look at the Environmental section and get opinion. Then run those changes by Environmental partners as well. 
Jason: Last sentence of document- What if there is a candidate that doesn’t agree with every point of the platform? (solved by taking out intro and kicker)
Max: why not specifically mention gun violence under Safety section? Also what are we gaining by having a platform, especially if there is a national platform? 
Rick: Does this leave us open for Republican attack. Can this not be a public facing document? If it is out there, not only do we need to defend it but candidates do as well. 
Robin: Language is general/broad so it does cover everything.
Lisa: If we don’t have a platform, or if a candidate doesn’t hold to the platform ideals once in office, how do we hold them accountable?
Stephon: this document is for us, not for the public in general. It gives us a “why”... a  purpose, or guide. 
Beth: Present as “value statements” not as a platform when discussing it. Need to rewrite it through that lens.
Send in comments ASAP for revisions. Table until next month.

